                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Personally, I think we're near the peak of our power. I can't think of a whole lot that Enchanters need in terms of new abilities or some such that wouldn't cause even more class-line deletion.  Anyway, nitpick/idea time...
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Crowd Control (Mesmerization)</span>
<br />

<br />
Instead of new, uber-leet mes's, I was thinking of something a bit, more, uh, indirect.  I'll cover it later, in the "Enchantment" section, but I think it's a nice idea myself.  There isn't a whole lot to be needed for us here, really, except maybe lower MR-checks.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Charming</span>
<br />

<br />
After Total Domination and Command of Druzzil, I seriously doubt we need anything given to us here, except perhaps the proposed AA to raise the Dire Charm level cap (for all classes that can get it).  It'd be almost a farce to give us a spell that would basically be an upgrade (either level or MR wise) to Command of Druzzil.  We all know where just CoD led, ask test.Xenosis! ;)  Not really being one for charm-soloing (I'm hopeless at it; I usually die at or near the 3rd mob pulled), or charming in general, I won't comment on the exp bit.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Enchantment</span>
<br />

<br />
First we get the following: PROC IMBUING.  These won't be your average procs, they'll be a bit more indirect offense by nature and role.
<br />

<br />
* lure-to-land MR-based "mesmerize self" proc-imbue: NPC has a chance of proc'ing an unresistable mes on itself for a short duration (1-2 ticks?); said mesmerize is a special version, meaning the anti-mesmerize flag won't affect the proc working on the NPC.  The general idea of this is basically to deal with NPCs that are meant to dish out the can o' whoop-ass yet aren't meant to be locked down with standard mesmerize spells.  This keeps them out of the fight, granted for a short time, but the only way they'll be locked down is if they do the damage they were meant to do by design.
<br />

<br />
* melee procs: here I was thinking of spells that will increase melee capabilities by some (small-to-medium) amount.  Namely, we get spells that will, say, "haste" a melee in a manner that they gain increased damage avoidance by means of improved checks on their dodge, parry, riposte, block, <span style="font-style: italic">whatever</span> melee skills.  The offensive/counter spells (MR based) would be to debuff these traits, making it easier to hit a given NPC.  In my world, Mages would get a group-based version of these types of buffs (damage mitigation, avoidance, etc.)
<br />

<br />
So in summary:
<br />

<br />
- special-mes type of proc, meant to keep nasty NPCs partly out of the fight but not really (the NPCs hit us for a lot of damage, and get locked-down for a short time)
<br />
- buffs/debuffs to melee and casting skills (chance to hit, resist checks, critical hits, riposte, etc. etc.); the debuffs would be a form of fear (would be checked for immunity via the anti-fear flag)
<br />
- spell-casting debuffs which have a chance of making NPCs fizzle: HINTHINTWINKWINK
<br />
- general proc-buffs: mana-steal, +hate, -hate, MR-based DD, etc. etc.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Spell Issues (Lines, Use, etc.)</span>
<br />

<br />
* buffs: consolidation of existing buffs, really.  For instance, I wouldn't mind seeing an upgrade of Arcane Rune or Zeb rune to include hp/mana regen or damage mitigation; other ideas include:
<br />

<br />
- fear/mes/charm (mind) resistance buffs; chances to resist/ignore those spells; kind of like DI has a chance to avoid death, here we have a chance to avoid negative CC (used by NPCs against you, or in PvP)
<br />

<br />
* reagents: personally I think emeralds should be a common reagent by now; I myself figure they should've started to use them for some Planar spells (Virtue and whatnot), but that's just me quibbling
<br />

<br />
* spell-handling (Alendar and Bounce/Reflect) - having it affect DoTs would be a big W, for sure.  As for Bounce and Reflect, does anyone really use these to great effect?  I myself would change them to be low-cast (2 seconds at most), very short-duration buffs which have a high chance of returning a spell <span style="font-weight: bold">OR</span> perhaps a long-duration, you pay mana to return the spell (based on the incoming spell's cost).  It's not like the classes that get Bounce and Reflect don't have methods of regaining that mana (gather mana, ToT, mind wrack, mod rods, harvest, and so on).  I also agree about the reagents.  I'm surprised the Vie line <span style="font-weight: bold">doesn't</span> require a reagent (if I had my say, it would win the peridot/emerald award).  That just threw balance out the window, somewhat.
<br />

<br />
* Visage line: I rarely use this lately; it seems I can't really be bothered to load it especially when SKs, for instance, can just plant the 12%, 10 minute buff on a melee, while we get a 4 <span style="font-weight: bold">tick</span>, inferior version.  That just seems odd.  And let's not forget the Warrior provoke line that's coming in soon. :)
<br />

<br />
* Shadow/Umbra line: I agree, avoidance just seems like a natural thing here
<br />

<br />
* Intellectual line (from Luclin):  To this I say, why?  Spell Casting Mastery and Mastery of the Past, for those that actually got them, pretty much make this idea already obsolete, and none of them have any use in the high end.  The only times I've ever casting Intellectual Superiority was for fun, and even still I seem to recall parses suggesting that they weren't really that useful to begin with.  Thoughts: change
<br />

<br />
* Gift of Magic line: KEI made Gift of Brilliance in particular obsolete; maybe a 5% mana preservation added with level/limit would be the best course here, and make them all group buffs (adjust mana cost as needed).  I don't use these ever, even at 60.  I rarely used them as it was, because the mana-cost vs. benefit just said "don't bother"
<br />

<br />
* Illusions: Froglok vs. Guktan = /headscratch; ok.. I'll pick either the old model after turning in a GLYPHED RUNE WORD, or use the new version which arguably looks far superior.  Just another thing to make me say "ooooookay then."  Other than that, --&gt;<span style="font-weight: bold">utility</span>&lt;-- illusions would get my attention as far as things go.  As the game stands now, you'd think they should just bag it and change the name of our spells to "Shapechange: &lt;whatever&gt;" or "Metamorph" etc.
<br />

<br />
Also, Illusion: Gender :)
<br />

<br />
* Stuns: I'm still on the fence here, but I surely wouldn't mind Largarn's becoming a new capability for us, as in it gaining its own spell line instead of just being our only single-target stun; instead of a stun you could make it a fear-based spell (meaning, a stun checked vs. mes or fear immunity instead of stun immunity; it's affecting the mind, not the body, folks)
<br />

<br />
* Sleep vs. Bliss - put Sleep's name back to Narcolepsy and change its function to the "proc" bit I mention above.  All done?
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Alternate Advancement</span>
<br />
- Passively improve spells against humanoid targets; we understand the human mind and how to manipulate it: for instance we could get a passive 20% nuking against human minds, lower resist rates on mes/charm, what have you.
<br />

<br />
- Illusion: Target; an AA because of the implications (faction wise) with this, according to the Devs.  Thus, something to work for, yet is controlled by refresh.
<br />

<br />
- Change Animation Empathy to be "/pet attack", "/pet follow, /pet guard" then "/pet back off" in that order of gaining.  In other words, being able to tell the pet to attack would be a basic thing, but finer control (overriding it and manipulating its behavior) would require more work.
<br />

<br />
Can't really think of much here aside from that, to be honest.  Haven't sat down about it.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
