                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think our crowd control abilities in the 'endgame' are too weak and unsuited to that environment.
<br />

<br />
The mobs on those raids have high mr, low hitpoints and a very high damage output. Low hitpoints mean the mobs arent going to stay mezzed for long - often less then the duration of the initial mez. If mezzing took a mob out of the equation for a minute or three it might be worth the extra risk, but thats rarely the case. At the same time, mezzing those mobs requires quick debuffs (putting more people at risk early) and even then more often then not the enchanter just ends up tanking the mob, and surviving that requires the attention of a good healer, most of the time using divine arbitration (love that skill). The problem is that the resist rate is so high and once you draw agro you're pretty much out of the fight - mob melee push with the damage you're taking from those mobs makes channeling very unlikely.
<br />

<br />
A bard is a better choice for actual mezzing - they dont draw agro from the resist as we do and 3 seconds later have the second mez attempt in. I takes longer for the enchanter to attempt a second mez even if he doesnt get agro. If a bard draws agro he'll have a much easier time getting a second mez through. Another option is just tankmezzing the mobs the whole time and skipping mez completely. We already have knights draw agro on the non-MA targets to keep them off debuffers/healers - with the low hp on those mobs its very feasible and probably less dangerous to just let them tankmezz a bit longer till the MA calls their mob as target (fewer people with high agro means the healer can concentrate on them better).
<br />

<br />
For LDoN raids the design is done - they should take the quick way and out and adjust the mr of those mobs downward if they are indeed intended to be enchanter-mezzed. Right now it seems to be intended to be tankmezzed, with an "but you CAN mez them"  excuse when we ask for our role on raids.
<br />

<br />
For future design, IF the encounters and zones are designed to be enchanter-mezzed (I hope so - but LDoN's design doesnt exactly give that impression), SoE either needs to design those mobs with more thought (less mr or lower damage output) or provide enchanters with alot more potent means of avoiding agro and/or dealing with it.
<br />
Enchanter mez needs to be specified here because bards get away with about everything mez-wise - the dangerous part about mezzing is drawing more agro then you can deal with, and bards simply dont draw noticeable agro with their mezzes. Maybe an AA that reduces chanter mez (and only mez) agro to bard levels, or new mez spells with variations on resist mod, casting/recast time, mana cost and duration (variations that bards dont get - the point is to create equality between bard/enc mezzing and right now 'not getting agro' is a damn huge advantage).
<br />

<br />

<br />
Another big factor for efficient crowd control is being able to identify the mobs you face and pick the right action from knowledge and experience - i.e. no mobs with the same names "randomly" immune mez or such.
<br />
Include mobs that are immune mez, that have high/low mr, that can only be charmed or rooted for crowd control etc - thats fun, IF you can learn the right methods for each mob. Trial and error for finding out if quad_1200_skeleton03 is rootable or mezzable today gets very old very fast. I want to be required to adjust my means of crowd control according to the situation. But I want to be able to learn and make the right choices faster and more efficient over time, not have the same random chance each time.
<br />
Thats something VT did right - a naming pattern that applied to all mobs and actually meant something. You could tell which mobs had high fire or cold resist, which might gate, which were mezzable with rapture only (pre-PoP) and which were immune.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=7110&alt=136431" target="_blank" class="postlink">Jennifer DeGartes</a>, Enchantress of <a href="http://www.vazaelle.dk" target="_blank" class="postlink">Caer Cadarn</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
